[Deal "E:.AKQJ8643.A5.QJ4 Q654.5.KT96.A865 K873.92.J8742.T3 AJT92.T7.Q3.K972"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2C pass 2D pass 2H pass 2NT pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "c007f6ec53e35479a770a7a5446f710d2e55b7cd0e57104ae094c445dd8f46f7"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/strong_2c"]
[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

You only have 20 points, but you have 9 playing tricks. You have two choices, open 4\H or open 2\C. Usually 4\H would show a slightly weaker hand than this, so you bid 2\C. Partner responds 2\D.  

Of course you bid your 8-card suit. But no jumping, just bid 2\H. Partner now says 2NT.  

Partner has between 3 and 7 points. Somewhere in those points might be the one trick you need, but you don't have any scientific way of finding out. So just bid 4\H and hope.(There it is, the \CT.)}

